# Influencer Marketing Analysis: Text and Image Features Driving Engagement

This project analyses Instagram posts from five influencers who had previously promoted Bath & Body Works. The aim was to understand which text and image features were associated with engagement, measured separately through likes and comments.

I led this group project as part of the Digital Marketing Intelligence course. My contribution included helping define the brand and influencer selection, coordinating the project, and running both the text and image analysis.

## Project objective

The purpose of the project was to move beyond surface-level engagement metrics and understand what kind of content performs better in influencer marketing. In particular, I wanted to examine whether caption features and visual characteristics could explain variation in likes and comments across influencer posts.

## Data

The dataset was built from publicly available Instagram posts.

It includes:
- 5 anonymized influencers
- 20 posts per influencer
- caption text
- likes
- comments
- text-based features such as emoji count, question marks, and hashtag use
- image-based features such as brightness, hue, saturation, and number of detected objects

To keep the focus on the analysis rather than individual creators, influencer identities are anonymized in this repository.

## Tools used

- **Python** for web scraping
- **R** for data analysis
- Libraries used include:
  - `tidyverse`
  - `tidytext`
  - `topicmodels`
  - `ggplot2`

## Methods

The analysis combined both text and image features.

Text analysis included:
- sentiment analysis
- topic modelling
- keyword analysis
- caption-level feature extraction

Image analysis included:
- brightness
- hue
- saturation
- object count

To study engagement, I used **linear regression models** with **interaction terms** and **quadratic terms**, with **likes** and **comments** modelled separately.

## Key findings

A few findings stood out clearly:

- Most individual text and image features were not strong predictors of engagement on their own.
- Generic positivity in captions was common, but it did not meaningfully explain engagement by itself.
- Using more hashtags did not improve performance.
- Some visual features mattered more than most text features.
- Saturation showed a **U-shaped relationship**, meaning very low or very high saturation performed better than moderate levels.
- Posts with a higher object count showed more informative engagement patterns in the model.
- Influencers with smaller followings but stronger engagement appeared more effective than larger creators with weaker audience interaction.

## Recommendations

Based on the results, I recommended the following:

- focus less on generic positive captions and more on each creator’s own content style
- avoid overloading captions with hashtags
- brief influencers based on what performs well for their specific audience rather than using one uniform content formula
- give stronger consideration to micro-influencers with higher engagement

## Repository contents

- `data/` – cleaned dataset used for analysis
- `scripts/` – scripts for scraping, cleaning, text analysis, image analysis, and modelling
- `slides/` – project presentation slides

## Note

This project was completed in an academic setting, but it was designed around a practical marketing question: how to better understand the drivers of influencer engagement using a combination of text and image analytics.
